Great Leader's Revival
London — — The Battle of Waterloo has been over for two hundred years, Napoleon's disastrous failure in that battle severely damaged France's self-esteem, to the extent that General de Gaulle didn't even mention it when writing the history of the French army.
Despite this, if you recognize "great" as a personal quality, then Napoleon and de Gaulle could both be called the greatest leaders in history.
Marx and Tolstoy would say that there is no such thing as a "great leader" in existence.
In Marx's view, the class struggle in France created an environment where such "grotesque mediocrities" like Napoleon could become heroes.
In Tolstoy's view, Napoleon was not a particularly outstanding general, his victories should be attributed to the courage and dedication of the French soldiers who won the Battle of Borodino.
Whether Napoleon was great or not, we need to clarify whether anyone can be described as great.
If the answer is yes, then who else can be described as great?
Political philosopher Isaiah Berlin believed that a great leader must meet two particularly important standards.
First, can this leader recognize historical trends?
Both Otto von Bismarck and his German compatriot Konrad Adenauer achieved this, as both heard "the rustling of the Almighty's cloak," to quote Bismarck's memorable phrase.
Secondly, was this leader able to make important decisions?
Of course, if a leader is forced to make decisions, they cannot be held accountable or gain praise solely because of that.
Therefore, the key is whether the leader has the opportunity to weigh the pros and cons and make the right decision for the country.
De Gaulle should therefore be included in any list of great leaders.
Almost single-handedly, he led France out of the downgraded zone after World War II.
After regaining power in 1958, he once again saved his country, suppressed two attempted coups, ended the Algerian War, and drafted the Fifth Republic Constitution.
Similar to British Prime Minister Winston Churchill, de Gaulle gave the French a new worldview, and laid the foundation for their position in the post-war global order.
In fact, the final impact of de Gaulle and Churchill establishing their respective national worldviews was a bit too great.
Their successors later looked at the world and their own country's role for years, in a way that was both a restraint on rational exploration and a distortion of decision-making.
As a result, the leaders of the two countries in the following years failed to achieve any comparable achievements of greatness.
But there is another British Prime Minister who can be compared to them: Margaret Thatcher, a very controversial figure, just as many people love her as they hate her.
Even her resignation 25 years ago was due to her own cabinet and party's counter-revolutionary activities.
However, it doesn't take everyone's approval to be a great leader.
In fact, even Thatcher's critics cannot deny her influence.
Aside from being the first female Prime Minister of the United Kingdom, she is also almost the first female Prime Minister of other countries in the world, Thatcher helped to turn around the UK's economic downturn.
Not to mention, her attack on the overly powerful trade unions increased its manageability at a time when the country seemed to slide into turmoil and chaos.
Given this, she undoubtedly has the right to be a candidate for "great leader".
Similarly, despite not being flawless, China's Deng Xiaoping also has the qualifications to be a great leader.
Aside from assisting Mao Zedong in doing evil, Deng also played a decisive role in ordering the 1989 Tiananmen Massacre.
But Deng also revitalized the market, leading China onto a development and prosperity path that would eventually allow billions of Chinese people to escape poverty.
Many people think that Singapore's founding father and long-time Prime Minister Lee Kuan Yew was very great, although he might have hoped to make a name for himself on a bigger stage.
In fact, the size of the nation seems not to affect one's ability to be a great leader.
I said that Luxembourg as a small country is unlikely to produce great leaders when I mentioned it, and I meant no offense, especially considering the country's overall political atmosphere is generally not very contentious.
The United States is vast in its territory, making it a suitable place for great leaders to emerge.
Some presidents have indeed achieved a lot.
Harry Truman and Dwight Eisenhower — — although not to be called intellectual giants — — demonstrated excellent judgment in establishing the post-war international order that has supported world peace for decades.
Others, including Ronald Reagan and Bill Clinton, have a high gift — — the ability to mobilize and the art of persuasion.
John F. Kennedy was well-rounded.
He completed a great task: resolving the Cuban Missile Crisis.
He had an unmatched gift for inspiring people; in fact, his assassination after his death further solidified the tradition he left behind.
In South Africa, no one has been called a great figure after the death of President Mandela, who embodied courage, authority, and broad-minded elegance.
In fact, he was the most charming and charismatic leader I have ever seen; the other two - former UN Secretary-General Kofi Annan and former US Secretary of State Colin Powell - are either not Africans or African Americans.
So today?
The only one who can call himself great is the de facto leader of the European Union, German Chancellor Angela Merkel.
Like former Chancellor Helmut Kohl, she was often underestimated at the beginning, but made few mistakes when making important decisions.
Kohl framed generous terms for the German unification; Merkel stood up to Putin during his invasion of Ukraine, and took a tolerant stance on the immigration crisis.
I think Marx and Tolstoy are wrong.
Politicians – the exercisers of political power – can change the course of events, whether for the better or worse.
Merkel is a clear example today, pointing out the direction for Europe to survive high-level crisis.
